19... Rxc3 { Black thinks they're trapping White's queen, but what happens if we "fall into" our opponent's tactic? } (19... Nxa1! $17 20. Qxa1 { Black is up an exchange and should be technically winning. Perhaps due to the closed nature of the position, though, White may be drawing if they play 50 precise moves! Therefore, we won't say that this position is clearly winning, but it's certainly better than the game continuation. }) 20. bxc3 { Any other move would be an admission of defeat. Besides, White really doesn't have any productive moves. } 20... Nxc3 { It looks like our queen is trapped. } { [%csl Gd1] } 21. Bc7!! $18 { But wait! The geometry somehow works out for us. The bishop can take two pieces in a row, and when the queen moves, the knight on b3 would no longer be protected. } 21... Qxc7 (21... Nxd1 22. Bxb6 { [%csl Gd8] } 22... Nxa1 (22... axb6 23. Raxd1 $18) 23. Bxd8 { [%csl Gd1,Ga1] } 23... Nxe3 24. fxe3 $18) (21... Nxa1 22. Bxb6 Nxd1 (22... axb6 23. Qxa1 $18) 23. Bxd8 Nxe3 24. fxe3 $18) 22. Qxb3 { And White is up a rook for two pawns. } 1-0


