50... f5 { Black misses White's cunning threat. How do you distract one of the pieces from controlling the a8 promotion square? } 51. Nf6!! { Threatening mate and distracting the rook from a8 } { [%csl Gh7] } (51. Bf3?? $19 Bxf3 { is no distraction as the knight protects the bishop. } { [%csl Gd4] }) (51. Kh4?? $19 { Trying to go for checkmate with the king, but this is too slow. } 51... Bd5 { Protecting the bishop from any Rxc6 sacrifices } 52. Kg5 Ne6+) 51... Rxf6 (51... f4+ { is just a distraction } 52. Kf2) (51... Rg8+ 52. Kh4! (52. Nxg8 { wins of course, but even faster is }) 52... Rg7 53. Rc8+ Be8 54. Rxe8+ Rg8 55. Rxg8#) 52. Rxc6 Rf8 (52... Nxc6 53. a8=Q+ $18) 53. Rb6! $18 { There's no stopping White's pawn from promoting without giving up the knight, in which case the rook + bishop + pawn should be enough to win against Black's rook + four pawns. } { [%cal Gb6b8] } (53. Rc7?? { Just allows Black to defend } 53... Ra8 $10 { White isn't losing because of the passed a-pawn, but of course a draw is a bad result when we were winning. }) 1-0


