21... Rb8 { Black misses White's shocking threat. Note that the Black king does not have too many squares to pass through. } 22. Qxf7+!! { Black has to give up signifcant material to survive. } (22. Bc4?? $17 { is too slow. } 22... Ne5! { [%csl Gf7] }) (22. Ng6?? $19 { doesn't threaten anything significant, while Black is crashing through on the queenside. } 22... b3!) 22... Kxf7 { Why did we sacrifice the queen? } (22... Kh7 23. Nh5! { [%csl Gg7] } 23... Rg8 24. Nf6+! Nxf6 25. Qg6+!! (25. Bxf6?? $14 Qe8! 26. Qxe8 Rxe8 27. Bxg7 Kxg7 28. Be2 { The endgame favors White, but of course this is not what we want. }) 25... Kh8 26. Bxf6 { [%cal Gg6h6] } 26... Bxf6 27. Qxh6#) 23. Bc4+!! Re6 (23... Kf8 24. Ng6# { The point! }) 24. fxe6+ (24. Bxe6+?? Ke8 $17 { White could have won the knight with 24. fxe6+. }) 24... Ke8 { The knight is pinned as Rd8# is threatened. Knowing that, do we have any better than immediately taking the knight? } 25. Nh5!! { The point is that if it were our move in this position, we have 1. Nxg7+ Kf8 2. e7+!, promoting on the next move. } { [%cal Gh5g7] } (25. exd7+? $18 { This move should still win, but it's not as accurate, and White has to keep playing very precisely to maintain their advantage. } 25... Bxd7) 25... Bc3!! { is a very tricky move. } 26. exd7+ (26. Rd3! { is also good, actually. But not as forcing. }) (26. Rhe1!! { is also good, making use of the Ng7+ - e7+ idea mentioned. But, again, not as forcing. } 26... Bxe1) (26. Rhf1! { with similar ideas to the main line, most probably just directly transposing } { [%cal Ge6d7,Gc4f7] }) 26... Bxd7 27. Rhf1!! { Threatening Bf7+ with a strong, game-winning discovery } (27. Nf6+?? $19 { Black gets too active with the queen. } 27... Bxf6 28. Bxf6?? b3 29. cxb3 Rxb3 30. Bxb3 Qxb3 $19) (27. Bb3! { This should also win, but it's more messy. } 27... e2! (27... Qc6? 28. bxc3 bxc3 $18)) 27... e2 28. Bf7+ { The only winning move } 28... Kf8 29. Bb3+ exf1=Q 30. Rxf1+ Ke8 31. Bxa4 Bxa4 { The bishop can now be safely taken as Black does not have enough attacking resources. However, even with only two Black pieces on the board, White must tread carefully. } 32. bxc3 bxc3+ 33. Kc1 { White just needs to pick up c3 and the position should be very easy to win from there. } 33... Rb2 34. Rf2 $18 { White needs to defend c2, after which we can enact our plan of taking c3. } { [%cal Gh4f6,Gf6c3] } 34... Ra2 35. Nf6+ { No matter where the king steps, White has a discovered check. } 35... Kf7 36. Ne4+ Kg6 37. Nxc3 $18 0-1


